# MONTLY
# Ensure the index is datetime (just in case)
doge.index = pd.to_datetime(doge.index)

# Extract year and month from the index
doge['Year'] = doge.index.year
doge['Month'] = doge.index.strftime('%b')

# Create the pivot table
pivot_df = doge.pivot_table(index='Month', columns='Year', values='Close', aggfunc='mean')

# Reorder the months
month_order = ['Jan', 'Feb', 'Mar', 'Apr', 'May', 'Jun',
               'Jul', 'Aug', 'Sep', 'Oct', 'Nov', 'Dec']
pivot_df = pivot_df.reindex(month_order)

plt.figure(figsize=(12, 7))

for year in pivot_df.columns:
    plt.plot(pivot_df.index, pivot_df[year], label=str(year), alpha=0.5)

monthly_avg = pivot_df.mean(axis=1)
plt.plot(pivot_df.index, monthly_avg, color='red', linewidth=3, label='Monthly Avg')

plt.title('Seasonal Plot: Monthly DOGE Prices with Average')
plt.xlabel('Month')
plt.ylabel('DOGE Price (USD)')
plt.legend(loc='center left', bbox_to_anchor=(1.0, 0.5), fontsize='small')
plt.grid(True)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Some important month:
May stands out with the highest average monthly price — notably in 2021 (green line), when DOGE peaked due to hype and social media (e.g., Elon Musk & SNL event).

November–December also shows some upward movement, possibly due to end-of-year trading activity.

July–September tends to have lower average prices, indicating a seasonal dip.

In [36]:
def find_best_ar_lag(series, max_lag=30, plot=True):
    """
    Automatically finds the best lag for an AR model based on AIC and BIC.

    Parameters:
    - series: pd.Series (e.g., differenced 'Close' prices)
    - max_lag: int, maximum lag to evaluate
    - plot: bool, whether to plot AIC/BIC

    Returns:
    - dict with best lags and full score table
    """
    aic_scores = []
    bic_scores = []
    lags = []

    warnings.filterwarnings("ignore")  # suppress convergence warnings

    for lag in range(1, max_lag + 1):
        try:
            model = AutoReg(series, lags=lag, old_names=False).fit()
            aic_scores.append(model.aic)
            bic_scores.append(model.bic)
            lags.append(lag)
        except Exception:
            continue

    results = pd.DataFrame({
        'Lag': lags,
        'AIC': aic_scores,
        'BIC': bic_scores
    }).set_index('Lag')

    best_aic_lag = results['AIC'].idxmin()
    best_bic_lag = results['BIC'].idxmin()

    if plot:
        results.plot(title='AIC and BIC Scores by Lag', figsize=(10, 4), marker='o')
        plt.ylabel('Score (lower is better)')
        plt.grid(True)
        plt.show()

    return {
        'best_aic_lag': best_aic_lag,
        'best_bic_lag': best_bic_lag,
        'results': results
    }

In [92]:
# === Forecast differenced values ===
forecast_steps = len(doge_test)
pred_diff = model.predict(start=len(doge_train), end=len(doge_train) + forecast_steps - 1)

# === Reconstruct forecasted Close prices from differencing ===
# Start from last actual known Close price
last_actual_close = doge_train['Close'].iloc[-1]
forecast_close = pred_diff.cumsum() + last_actual_close

# === Align actual Close from test data ===
actual_close = doge_test['Close']

# === Combine everything for plotting ===
full_close = pd.concat([doge_train['Close'], actual_close])
full_forecast = pd.Series(data=forecast_close.values, index=actual_close.index)

# === Plot ===
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 5))
plt.plot(full_close, label="Original DOGE Close")
plt.plot(actual_close, label="Actual Test Close")
plt.plot(full_forecast, label="Forecasted Close")
plt.title("DOGE Close: Actual vs Forecast")
plt.xlabel("Date")
plt.ylabel("Price (USDT)")
plt.legend()
plt.grid(True)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Underfitting is expected since AR is simple model
